{"key":"post-12430662","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12430662</id>\n<content>If you squeeze &lt;i&gt;really hard&lt;/i&gt;, a small stream should flow for only a second or two and then stop.&amp;nbsp; There's a difference in squeezing strength between someone who works in an office and a construction worker.&amp;nbsp; The descriptions given are to get you through the first few projects, after which time every&amp;nbsp; grower realizes exactly how moist a substrate should be.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The fluffier a given substrate is, the more water will squeeze out.&amp;nbsp; That's why with sawdust, I adjust so not one single drop comes out when squeezed as hard as I can.&amp;nbsp; However, with coir, compost, manure, etc., adjust as mentioned in the first paragraph above and demonstrated on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Casing-Layer-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;casing layer video clip&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12430874</next>\n<prev>12430515</prev>\n<first>12430093</first>\n<last>12430996</last>\n<when>1271859360</when>\n<utime>04/21/10 05:16 PM</utime>\n</post>"}